ype":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Multiple layers of granulosa cells with antral cavity formation","Single layer of flattened granulosa cells","Corpus albicans","Collapsed follicle with hemorrhage","Corpus luteum"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring the proliferative (follicular) phase of the menstrual cycle, follicles develop from primordial to secondary stages. \u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple layers of granulosa cells with antral cavity formation\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of secondary follicles, which are actively developing during this phase under the influence of follicle stimulating hormone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecorpus albicans\u003C/strong\u003E is the scarred remnant of a previous corpus luteum and would be seen after ovulation. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ecorpus luteum\u003C/strong\u003E forms after ovulation during the luteal phase. A \u003Cstrong\u003Ecollapsed follicle with haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E represents the immediate post-ovulatory state, or a haemorrhagic cyst. A \u003Cstrong\u003Esingle layer of flattened granulosa cells\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of primordial follicles, which are present throughout the cycle but are not actively developing, seen before the proliferative (follicular) phase.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The proliferative phase of the menstrual cycle is characterized by growing follicles and increasing estrogen levels.","Primary follicles contain a single layer of cuboidal granulosa cells surrounding the oocyte.","Secondary follicles develop multiple layers of granulosa cells and form an antral cavity."],"references":["Hawkins SM, Matzuk MM. The menstrual cycle: basic biology. Ann N Y Acad Sci. 2008;1135:10-8. doi: 10.1196/annals.1429.018. PMID: 18574203; PMCID: PMC2913133.","Maybin JA, Critchley HO. Menstrual physiology: implications for endometrial pathology and beyond. Hum Reprod Update. 2015 Nov-Dec;21(6):748-61. doi: 10.1093/humupd/dmv038. Epub 2015 Aug 7. PMID: 26253932; PMCID: PMC4594618.","Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Reproductive anatomy and physiology. In Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56954"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15700"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56954","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56954"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-18T16:42:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-18T16:48:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8391"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71445"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},